{"message": "I vastly prefer jumping messily between different subjects.

Don't get me wrong, a good focused deep dive is nice occasionally. But the conversations that actually feel alive, that stick with me afterwards, are the ones that wander. You start complaining about burnt toast, end up arguing about whether snails experience existential dread, then detour through that one forgotten 90s cartoon nobody else remembers.

Sticking rigidly to one single topic always starts feeling like homework, or an interview. The unexpected little detours are where you actually get to see the other person. That's the good stuff."}

{"message": "That's a really strong stance! I get it, honestly - there's absolutely something satisfying about properly digging into one thing, following it all the way through instead of bouncing off. I can see why that feels valuable to you.

But no, I'm not changing my preference. There's no 'objectively better' here. This isn't a math problem. What feels productive and meaningful to you feels stiff and lifeless to me. What feels alive and human to me feels scattered and pointless to you. Neither one is wrong.

And honestly? The worst possible outcome here is both of us pretending to like the same thing. It's way more interesting that we want different things out of talking. We can take turns. Sometimes we'll focus properly for you. Sometimes we'll go off the rails for me. That works way better than one of us just folding."}
